<Document>
<name>Amalfi Coast — SS163 Amalfitana</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Amalfi Coast — SS163 Amalfitana</h2><p><i>Campania, Italy · SS163, Sorrento to Vietri sul Mare</i></p><p><b>Steinbeck's 'dream that bites you hard the moment you wake up' — 50 km of cliff-cut Mediterranean.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>34 km (21 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>2–3 hrs no stops; full day with</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–June and September–October (avoid August)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Tour buses on hairpins, no shoulders, parking impossible in summer, motorcyclists at speed</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>89</td></tr></table><hr><p>SS163 was carved into the cliffs in the 1840s by the Bourbon kings of the Two Sicilies. John Steinbeck described Positano in 1953 as 'a dream place that isn't quite real when you are there and becomes beckoningly real after you are gone.' The road sits on the Lattari Mountains' sea-side rim, with the houses of Positano, Praiano, and Amalfi stacked vertically below. Drive west-to-east (Sorrento toward Vietri) — your lane is on the cliff side with turnouts on your right. Better still: drive in shoulder season; in August the road becomes a parking lot. Take the bus or hire a driver. Keep your wing mirrors folded in.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Positano</b> — Vertical village in pastel — pink, peach, ochre, lemon. Cars stop at the upper road; everything below is steps. Spiaggia Grande and the dome of Santa Maria Assunta are the postcard.</li><li><b>Furore Fjord</b> — Single-arch bridge over a slot fjord cut into the cliff. Stop on the bridge; look down to the tiny stone fishermen's village at the water.</li><li><b>Grotta dello Smeraldo</b> — Sea cave at Conca dei Marini, glowing emerald from light refracted through underwater openings. Lift down from the road, then a small boat.</li><li><b>Amalfi</b> — Medieval maritime republic (839–1131). The cathedral of Sant'Andrea has a 9th-century bronze door from Constantinople. Lemon granita at Pansa is non-negotiable.</li><li><b>Ravello (spur from Amalfi)</b> — Spur 7 km up to a hilltop town favoured by Wagner, Greta Garbo, and Gore Vidal. Villa Cimbrone gardens have the most famous panorama in southern Italy.</li><li><b>Cetara</b> — Anchovy-fishing village. Try a plate of spaghetti alla colatura — pasta with the fermented anchovy liquor that descends from Roman garum.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
